    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-11-08T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-11-08T07:00:00-05:00" n="171"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d171">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.5131/908: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in France (<persName type="from"
                            >Marriner</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-11-08T12:00:00+00:00"
                            >November 8, 1932—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received November 8—9:15
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>640. My 634, November 2, 3 p.m.<note n="67" xml:id="d171fn67">Not printed.</note>
                    I am pleased to inform you that after considerable effort on the Embassy’s part,
                    and provided the United States Treasury regulation regarding the free admission
                    of dress samples is issued on the same day, the Ministries of Foreign Affairs
                    and Commerce have agreed to the issuance of the copper decree. The consent of
                    the French Ministry of Finance is still required and its answer is expected
                    today or tomorrow. Is this arrangement agreeable to you and how many days’
                    notice would you require?</p>
                <p>It is understood that the Treasury regulation will render the provision 3 of
                    section 308 of the Tariff Act applicable to samples of wearing apparel.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Marriner</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
